WEBVTT

00:00.709 --> 00:04.003
<i> - For two seasons, America's</i>
<i> most talented bladesmiths</i>

00:04.046 --> 00:06.005
<i> have faced off</i>
<i> in the ultimate competition...</i>

00:06.048 --> 00:07.840
- Getting pretty hot
in the kitchen.

00:07.883 --> 00:10.592
<i> - Making some of history's</i>
<i> deadliest weapons.</i>

00:10.636 --> 00:12.678
<i> Now, with the stakes</i>
<i> higher than ever,</i>

00:12.722 --> 00:14.346
<i> a new batch of bladesmiths</i>

00:14.390 --> 00:16.181
<i> enter the Forge</i>
<i> to test their skills.</i>

00:16.225 --> 00:17.975
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Watch out. Watch out. Watch out.

00:18.019 --> 00:19.435
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

00:19.478 --> 00:22.271
<i> - Only one will</i>
<i> take home $10,000</i>

00:22.314 --> 00:25.941
<i> and be crowned</i>
<i> "Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

00:25.985 --> 00:28.902
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

00:28.946 --> 00:35.367
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:35.411 --> 00:37.202
<i> - My name's Allen Newberry.</i>

00:37.246 --> 00:39.413
<i> I've been making knives</i>
<i> for about nine years.</i>

00:39.457 --> 00:44.084
I am a stay-at-home dad/
custom-knife maker.

00:44.128 --> 00:46.128
- I'm Chase Wilder.
I'm 19 years old.

00:46.172 --> 00:48.297
And I've been bladesmithing
for about five years.

00:48.340 --> 00:50.090
<i> I'm the oldest of six kids.</i>

00:50.134 --> 00:51.925
<i> I have taught my brothers</i>
<i> how to do</i>

00:51.969 --> 00:53.927
<i> a little bit of blacksmithing,</i>
<i> but at the same time,</i>

00:53.971 --> 00:55.512
I've got to tell 'em
to keep away from the fire,

00:55.556 --> 00:56.764
and, you know,
sparks are flying.

00:56.807 --> 00:58.599
<i> - My name is Mike Shindel.</i>

00:58.642 --> 01:02.061
I'm from what used to be
Soviet Union.

01:02.104 --> 01:05.022
<i> I came to U.S.</i>
<i> as a political refugee.</i>

01:05.066 --> 01:06.648
<i> I'm here to prove to myself</i>

01:06.692 --> 01:09.526
<i> that I've accomplished</i>
<i> something.</i>

01:09.570 --> 01:11.361
<i> - My name's Clayton Cowart,</i>

01:11.405 --> 01:13.030
<i> and I've been bladesmithing</i>
<i> for seven years.</i>

01:13.074 --> 01:15.449
<i> I'm very blunt.</i>
<i> I have very little filter.</i>

01:15.493 --> 01:17.743
People either like me,
or they don't.

01:17.787 --> 01:19.912
There's not really
an in-between.

01:19.955 --> 01:22.247
- Welcome to the Forge,
bladesmiths.

01:22.291 --> 01:24.708
You're here for three rounds
of blade-making competition

01:24.752 --> 01:27.086
designed to push your skills
to the limit.

01:27.129 --> 01:29.129
At the end of each round,
you will hand your work over

01:29.173 --> 01:31.965
to our panel of expert judges--

01:32.009 --> 01:34.802
master bladesmith Jason Knight,

01:34.845 --> 01:38.305
historic-weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

01:38.349 --> 01:41.517
and last, edged-weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:41.560 --> 01:43.227
Ultimately, they decide
which of you

01:43.270 --> 01:45.104
is the "Forged in Fire" champion

01:45.147 --> 01:47.439
who leaves here
with a check for 10 grand.

01:47.483 --> 01:48.816
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:48.859 --> 01:51.068
Are you ready to do battle?
- Ready.

01:51.112 --> 01:52.569
- Well, if you're going
into battle,

01:52.613 --> 01:54.613
you'll probably want
something like this.

01:54.657 --> 01:56.824
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:56.867 --> 01:58.784
<i> [heavy rock music]</i>

01:58.828 --> 02:00.619
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:00.663 --> 02:01.912
- [scoffs, chuckles]

02:01.956 --> 02:04.915
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:04.959 --> 02:06.750
- Am I gonna have to wear
a suit of armor

02:06.794 --> 02:08.669
to forge a knife?

02:08.712 --> 02:10.254
- Your first-round challenge

02:10.297 --> 02:12.923
is to combine steel
from that suit of armor

02:12.967 --> 02:14.925
with the high-carbon steel
on your anvil

02:14.969 --> 02:17.052
to forge a signature blade.

02:17.096 --> 02:20.180
How you choose to do this
is entirely up to you.

02:20.224 --> 02:21.723
Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:21.767 --> 02:23.517
you'll be putting handles
on your blades

02:23.561 --> 02:25.310
to turn them
into fully functional weapons

02:25.354 --> 02:28.188
that will then be tested
for strength and durability--

02:28.232 --> 02:33.110
piercing through steel
and slicing through apples.

02:33.154 --> 02:36.155
The blades themselves must fall
within the following parameters.

02:36.198 --> 02:38.157
<i> The length of the blade,</i>
<i> not including the tang,</i>

02:38.200 --> 02:40.909
<i> must fall between</i>
<i> 10 and 14 inches.</i>

02:40.953 --> 02:42.703
<i> The overall length</i>
<i> of your weapon</i>

02:42.746 --> 02:46.874
<i> must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

02:46.917 --> 02:48.458
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

02:48.502 --> 02:50.836
You'll have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:50.880 --> 02:53.255
I remind you
that when the time runs out,

02:53.299 --> 02:55.257
one of you will have
to surrender his weapon

02:55.301 --> 02:56.800
and leave the Forge.

02:56.844 --> 02:58.010
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:58.053 --> 02:59.553
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:59.597 --> 03:02.055
Your ten-minute design window
starts now.

03:02.099 --> 03:04.975
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:05.019 --> 03:07.311
Well, Dave,
how thick is that steel?

03:07.354 --> 03:10.105
- That armor's made
out of an 18-gauge steel.

03:10.149 --> 03:11.356
- It's very, very thin.

03:11.400 --> 03:13.025
- The hardest part is gonna be

03:13.068 --> 03:14.568
layering up enough
of that steel

03:14.612 --> 03:16.987
and making sure
you've got a good weld.

03:17.031 --> 03:19.865
<i> - I'm drawing</i>
<i> an Americanized tanto.</i>

03:19.909 --> 03:21.408
<i> The tanto tip is gonna give me</i>

03:21.452 --> 03:22.910
<i> the best bet</i>
<i> at piercing the metal</i>

03:22.953 --> 03:24.786
<i> without damaging the tip.</i>

03:24.830 --> 03:27.122
I'm gonna make a great blade
to stand out, I guess,

03:27.166 --> 03:28.916
and what else do you do?

03:28.959 --> 03:31.084
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:31.128 --> 03:35.714
<i> - I'm going to make</i>
<i> a recurved clip-point blade.</i>

03:35.758 --> 03:37.633
<i> Design is my strong point.</i>

03:37.676 --> 03:39.343
<i> I'm a part-time bladesmith</i>

03:39.386 --> 03:43.305
and a part-time creator-producer
of animation, cartoons.

03:43.349 --> 03:44.848
<i> - It's not every day</i>
<i> you get to pull apart</i>

03:44.892 --> 03:46.350
<i> a suit of armor.</i>

03:46.393 --> 03:47.976
<i> I am definitely</i>
<i> a history buff myself,</i>

03:48.020 --> 03:49.102
<i> so getting to work</i>
<i> with something like this</i>

03:49.146 --> 03:51.104
is extra special.

03:51.148 --> 03:53.232
<i> So I'm designing</i>
<i> a drop-point chopping knife.</i>

03:53.275 --> 03:54.858
<i> I want to have</i>
<i> that spear point</i>

03:54.902 --> 03:57.110
so that I could, you know,
do any sort of stabbing

03:57.154 --> 03:59.112
that was necessary
and then still some slicing.

03:59.156 --> 04:00.989
- Which pieces
would you go for, Dave?

04:01.033 --> 04:02.950
- The problem
is they're so rounded,

04:02.993 --> 04:05.619
the more you have to work
to flatten those pieces out,

04:05.663 --> 04:07.955
the more you're putting in
to just your prep work.

04:07.998 --> 04:09.581
I'd probably shoot
for the legs.

04:09.625 --> 04:11.291
- Probably use that codpiece,

04:11.335 --> 04:13.543
because that's got to be
the toughest piece on there.

04:13.587 --> 04:14.836
[laughter]

04:14.880 --> 04:17.089
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:17.132 --> 04:18.882
<i> - I'm drawing four</i>
<i> different blade designs,</i>

04:18.926 --> 04:21.009
<i> and I'm hoping once I have</i>
<i> this chunk of metal,</i>

04:21.053 --> 04:22.803
<i> that I will know which one</i>

04:22.846 --> 04:24.888
<i> is the knife</i>
<i> that I'm gonna make.</i>

04:24.932 --> 04:26.515
<i> If I was the next</i>
<i> "Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

04:26.558 --> 04:27.516
my family would go crazy.

04:27.559 --> 04:28.600
They'd love it.

04:28.644 --> 04:31.061
There'd probably be cake.

04:31.105 --> 04:34.523
- Bladesmiths! Your ten-minute
design window is now closed.

04:34.566 --> 04:36.900
Your three-hour forge time
starts...

04:36.944 --> 04:39.111
now.

04:39.154 --> 04:40.946
We didn't give them
enough high-carbon steel

04:40.990 --> 04:42.364
to meet the blade requirements,

04:42.408 --> 04:43.949
so they're gonna need
a lot of steel

04:43.993 --> 04:45.701
off of this suit of armor
over here.

04:45.744 --> 04:49.246
- The bar stock's, what, 2,
2 1/2 inches long?

04:49.290 --> 04:51.415
<i> So I know</i>
<i> that I need to use a lot</i>

04:51.458 --> 04:52.958
of knight-in-shining-armor guy
if you want to get

04:53.002 --> 04:54.251
<i> 10 to 14 inches out of that.</i>

04:54.295 --> 04:56.086
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:56.130 --> 04:58.422
<i> - I think the hardest part</i>
<i> of this challenge</i>

04:58.465 --> 05:02.509
is actually getting the armor,
you know, prepped

05:02.553 --> 05:03.719
and having it stick.

05:03.762 --> 05:05.804
[metal clangs]
- [laughs]

05:05.848 --> 05:06.972
I like that technique.

05:07.016 --> 05:08.473
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:08.517 --> 05:10.892
- So Clayton has
that one leg piece.

05:13.897 --> 05:16.148
- Next, after I flatten
the pieces of the armor,

05:16.191 --> 05:19.276
I take them to the band saw
and cut them down to size

05:19.320 --> 05:21.153
and then tack-weld
the whole thing together

05:21.196 --> 05:24.197
into a billet.

05:24.241 --> 05:27.200
Right now I'm trying to bring
this billet up to forge temp.

05:27.244 --> 05:28.201
I'm gonna start
to consolidate it

05:28.245 --> 05:29.578
and see how much material I have

05:29.621 --> 05:31.288
to see if I can meet
the requirements,

05:31.332 --> 05:32.664
otherwise I'm gonna have to go
back to the armor

05:32.708 --> 05:33.957
and pull some more pieces
to add to it.

05:34.001 --> 05:35.584
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:35.627 --> 05:39.171
- Clayton seems like
he's ahead of the pack.

05:39.214 --> 05:41.006
[machinery whirring]

05:41.050 --> 05:42.716
<i> - I drew, I think,</i>
<i> four designs,</i>

05:42.760 --> 05:45.135
and I figured
once I had my chunk of steel

05:45.179 --> 05:47.137
it would tell me
what it wanted to be.

05:47.181 --> 05:50.349
- So Allen cut up
his hardenable steel.

05:50.392 --> 05:51.892
- He's gonna forge-weld it
back together

05:51.935 --> 05:55.020
and throw the pieces of armor
in between.

05:55.064 --> 05:57.356
- That's okay
as long as he's got

05:57.399 --> 05:59.399
a hardenable piece
in the center.

05:59.443 --> 06:02.027
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:02.071 --> 06:02.986
- Ah, [bleep].

06:03.030 --> 06:05.072
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:05.115 --> 06:07.407
My plan is to use armor

06:07.451 --> 06:11.828
and put the high-carbon core
right in between.

06:11.872 --> 06:13.246
I hope it sticks, man.

06:13.290 --> 06:15.082
I'm rushing as I'm welding,

06:15.125 --> 06:16.875
because, you know, the clock
just, you know, ticking.

06:16.919 --> 06:18.794
Ah.

06:18.837 --> 06:20.629
I saw the end start to pop.

06:20.672 --> 06:23.298
It's not welding.
I say to myself--

06:23.342 --> 06:26.009
"Stay calm.
Try to work it through."

06:26.053 --> 06:27.177
But I'm panicking.

06:27.221 --> 06:29.096
I got to make it stick.

06:29.139 --> 06:30.514
<i> - He's got a weld on the side</i>
<i> of that billet</i>

06:30.557 --> 06:32.224
<i> that's not closing up,</i>

06:32.267 --> 06:34.643
and he's trying to use the flux
to clean it out.

06:34.686 --> 06:36.436
It's not going to do it.

06:36.480 --> 06:38.563
- If it doesn't stick
the first time,

06:38.607 --> 06:40.399
all the extra fluxing
and fluxing

06:40.442 --> 06:42.025
is not gonna make it stick.

06:42.069 --> 06:43.652
- Either grind that piece off

06:43.695 --> 06:46.154
or cut the scale
that's built up in there out

06:46.198 --> 06:47.406
and then close it up again.

06:47.449 --> 06:49.116
- [exhales sharply]

06:49.159 --> 06:51.410
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:51.453 --> 06:53.370
- So I've got three pieces
of the armor,

06:53.414 --> 06:56.248
and then I've got two pieces
that I got from my carbon stock.

06:56.291 --> 06:57.332
<i> Hopefully, that'll be enough.</i>

06:57.376 --> 06:59.000
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:59.044 --> 07:01.002
<i> - Chase actually chiseled</i>
<i> his billet,</i>

07:01.046 --> 07:02.629
<i> folded it over,</i>

07:02.673 --> 07:04.464
and he's now
forge-welding it again,

07:04.508 --> 07:06.508
so he's doing multiple,
multiple layers.

07:06.552 --> 07:08.468
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:08.512 --> 07:11.221
- The word for today
is "flux."

07:11.265 --> 07:13.890
- I never realized
that I used all that much flux.

07:13.934 --> 07:17.519
- People will do what they know,
but do they know why?

07:17.563 --> 07:18.895
- It's just kind of
how I do it.

07:18.939 --> 07:21.606
- It is like
seasoning your steak.

07:21.650 --> 07:23.233
- I figure, you know,
it's better to have too much

07:23.277 --> 07:24.359
than too little.

07:24.403 --> 07:27.362
- I understand
fluxing the edge,

07:27.406 --> 07:29.656
where you can see
all the layers.

07:29.700 --> 07:31.950
What is the point
of fluxing the flat part

07:31.994 --> 07:34.202
where you can't see the edges?

07:34.246 --> 07:35.912
- I don't want
to fluxing talk about it.

07:35.956 --> 07:37.289
- [laughing]

07:37.332 --> 07:38.623
- Fluxing up
the whole situation.

07:38.667 --> 07:39.624
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:43.005 --> 07:46.506
- You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work!

07:46.550 --> 07:47.966
- Things go quick.

07:48.010 --> 07:49.384
- You know
what's very interesting?

07:49.428 --> 07:51.261
You see the pace
that Clayton's going,

07:51.305 --> 07:53.847
and then you see the complete
opposite with Allen.

07:53.891 --> 07:55.891
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:55.934 --> 07:58.101
- All right, have I mentioned
I'm a terrible welder?

07:58.145 --> 08:00.812
<i> I am wanting to do</i>
<i> a "brute de forge"-type knife</i>

08:00.856 --> 08:04.316
<i> where you leave a rough finish</i>
<i> on the blade.</i>

08:04.359 --> 08:06.735
I think it's gonna set apart
the blade that I'm making.

08:06.778 --> 08:09.070
<i> The clock</i>
<i> is definitely ticking,</i>

08:09.114 --> 08:12.073
<i> but it's still nice</i>
<i> and manageable.</i>

08:12.117 --> 08:14.743
- I haven't seen
this ancient parable

08:14.786 --> 08:19.206
of the tortoise and the hare
played out in this arena before.

08:19.249 --> 08:21.541
- Let's hope it's the tortoise
that wins the race.

08:21.585 --> 08:23.877
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:23.921 --> 08:26.505
- Our smiths are really going
through the water today.

08:26.548 --> 08:28.715
Good thing.
It's hot on the floor.

08:28.759 --> 08:30.967
<i> - It's not hot in the Forge.</i>
<i> I'm an Arizonian.</i>

08:31.011 --> 08:33.595
Last week,
it hit 128 at my house,

08:33.639 --> 08:35.263
and inside of my shed,

08:35.307 --> 08:37.891
<i> during forge-welding,</i>
<i> we hit 138.</i>

08:37.935 --> 08:39.017
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:39.061 --> 08:40.685
- I'm concerned for Chase.

08:40.729 --> 08:42.896
He's running out of fluids.

08:42.940 --> 08:44.397
- [breathes heavily]
- Drink water!

08:44.441 --> 08:45.815
<i> - I'm from Michigan.</i>

08:45.859 --> 08:47.943
It never gets
this hot there, ever.

08:47.986 --> 08:50.654
So it's definitely starting
to take a toll on me.

08:50.697 --> 08:52.364
- When it gets hot
in a place like this,

08:52.407 --> 08:54.824
you lose your mind,
and your butt will follow.

08:54.868 --> 08:58.119
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:58.163 --> 08:59.371
<i> - I'm just running around</i>

08:59.414 --> 09:01.164
like one
of my cartoon characters,

09:01.208 --> 09:03.416
like a chicken without a head.

09:03.460 --> 09:05.835
- Mike has just ground off
the edges of his billet

09:05.879 --> 09:08.088
to see
if his forge weld held up.

09:08.131 --> 09:12.884
- I think it stuck together,
but I hope I have enough length.

09:12.928 --> 09:17.347
I'm right on the cusp
of not having enough material.

09:17.391 --> 09:20.225
I don't know, man.
Good enough?

09:20.269 --> 09:21.893
- It's good
to see Mike measuring,

09:21.937 --> 09:23.979
but he's shaking his head.

09:24.022 --> 09:25.647
- It looks like
his blade's the right length,

09:25.691 --> 09:27.065
but there's no handle on it.

09:27.109 --> 09:29.276
- I'm worried,
you know, big-time.

09:29.319 --> 09:31.111
[exhales sharply]

09:31.154 --> 09:33.071
<i> - Leading up to the quench,</i>

09:33.115 --> 09:34.406
<i> I'm feeling really,</i>
<i> really good.</i>

09:34.449 --> 09:35.699
I had
a real even spine thickness,

09:35.742 --> 09:36.908
which is rather important

09:36.952 --> 09:39.035
<i>to keeping your blade straight.</i>

09:39.079 --> 09:41.705
- Clayton has quenched.
Let's see if he's happy with it.

09:41.748 --> 09:44.624
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:44.668 --> 09:46.710
- Nope, not happy.

09:46.753 --> 09:49.421
- It's like a Kentucky road--
not a straight line in sight.

09:49.464 --> 09:51.506
[laughs]

09:51.550 --> 09:54.926
<i> As long as that blade doesn't</i>
<i> drop below 400 degrees,</i>

09:54.970 --> 09:57.929
I have a pretty good chance of
getting it straight in the vise.

09:57.973 --> 10:01.016
- I wouldn't play that game.
That's a risky game to play.

10:01.059 --> 10:03.184
<i> - Once I cross that</i>
<i> 400-degree barrier, though,</i>

10:03.228 --> 10:05.770
that blade breaking
is almost a guaranteed thing.

10:05.814 --> 10:07.314
- No, no, no.

10:07.357 --> 10:10.025
- Clayton is really,
really pushing his luck

10:10.068 --> 10:13.194
with his blade.
- This has got me worried.

10:13.238 --> 10:14.904
- That blade temperature's
really dropping.

10:14.948 --> 10:16.656
- This is where
he's gonna break it.

10:16.700 --> 10:20.869
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:24.499 --> 10:27.459
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:27.502 --> 10:31.046
- My blade came out
rather warped from the quench.

10:31.089 --> 10:34.341
As long as that blade doesn't
drop below 400 degrees,

10:34.384 --> 10:36.843
I have a pretty good chance
of getting it straight.

10:36.887 --> 10:39.471
Oh, come on.
- He's gonna break it.

10:39.514 --> 10:43.475
- Clayton is really, really
pushing his luck with his blade.

10:43.518 --> 10:45.810
- It's all a complete guess.
I'm not a thermometer.

10:45.854 --> 10:48.438
<i> But I'm extremely confident</i>
<i> that I can still pull</i>

10:48.482 --> 10:49.689
a little bit of that warp out.

10:49.733 --> 10:51.650
- Just makes my skin crawl.

10:51.693 --> 10:53.485
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

