Let's see what we can do
with less than five minutes

22:13.875 --> 22:15.082
for handle shaping.

22:15.126 --> 22:17.084
- Don't give us
a wooden block.

22:17.128 --> 22:18.711
- This just seems crazy to me.

22:18.755 --> 22:20.713
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:20.757 --> 22:25.009
I have never shaped a handle
at this speed before in my life.

22:25.053 --> 22:27.219
- Ten, nine,

22:27.263 --> 22:28.971
eight, seven,

22:29.015 --> 22:31.015
six, five,

22:31.059 --> 22:32.975
four, three,

22:33.019 --> 22:36.395
two, one!

22:36.439 --> 22:38.773
Shut down your machines!
Return to your anvil!

22:38.816 --> 22:41.150
Your work is done!

22:41.194 --> 22:43.194
- For a 4-minute handle,
I'm impressed.

22:43.237 --> 22:45.946
I just wish I had
a 4-minute-and-30-second handle.

22:45.990 --> 22:47.698
- [scoffs]

22:47.742 --> 22:50.326
I've never done anything
so fast.

22:50.370 --> 22:52.787
Never.
I forgot to breathe.

22:52.830 --> 22:55.915
You know, it's like, [bleep].

22:55.958 --> 22:56.916
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:56.959 --> 22:58.000
- Bladesmiths.

22:58.044 --> 22:59.710
I will be testing the strength

22:59.754 --> 23:02.421
and durability
of your blade's tip

23:02.465 --> 23:05.800
by attempting to drive it
through this steel-plate armor.

23:05.843 --> 23:07.593
Are you guys nervous?

23:07.637 --> 23:10.304
- Very.
- Allen, you're up first.

23:10.348 --> 23:17.186
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:25.822 --> 23:28.239
Allen,
you still have a tip there.

23:28.282 --> 23:29.949
That's good news.
- That is good news.

23:29.992 --> 23:32.243
- I'm impressed
with how thin this tip is,

23:32.286 --> 23:35.621
and you don't have
any issues there, so...

23:35.665 --> 23:38.207
Well done.
- Thank you.

23:38.251 --> 23:40.209
- Mike, ready?
- Yes, sir.

23:40.253 --> 23:42.503
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:42.547 --> 23:45.381
<i> I'm thinking, please, please,</i>
<i> you know, don't break.</i>

23:45.425 --> 23:48.342
<i> Don't break.</i>
<i> Just go through it, you know?</i>

23:48.386 --> 23:49.677
<i> [laughs]</i>

23:49.720 --> 23:52.847
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:52.890 --> 23:53.931
[exhales sharply]

23:53.975 --> 23:56.851
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:56.894 --> 24:00.771
- Mike, my biggest concern
was the blade coming apart

24:00.815 --> 24:02.440
where you had to reweld it.

24:02.483 --> 24:05.109
- Yeah.
- But it held up.

24:05.153 --> 24:06.152
- Good deal.

24:06.195 --> 24:07.987
- Clayton, ready?

24:08.030 --> 24:08.988
- I am.

24:09.031 --> 24:15.870
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

24:23.379 --> 24:25.254
Clayton,
it's like I didn't even hit it.

24:25.298 --> 24:29.341
My concern was that you used
burl material for your handle

24:29.385 --> 24:31.218
and you burned it through.
- Yep.

24:31.262 --> 24:34.638
- I've never seen that
stay together, except for today.

24:34.682 --> 24:36.223
- All right.
- Yeah.

24:36.267 --> 24:39.018
Well done.
- Thank you.

24:39.061 --> 24:41.979
- Bladesmiths, to see how sharp
the edge of your blade is,

24:42.023 --> 24:45.691
I will attempt to cut through
all these apples with one slice.

24:45.735 --> 24:47.276
Allen, you're up first.

24:47.320 --> 24:54.158
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:00.124 --> 25:03.042
Well, Allen, because of your
edge geometry being uneven,

25:03.085 --> 25:05.794
it did want
to lift up on the cut.

25:05.838 --> 25:08.380
But it's a sharp blade.
- All right.

25:08.424 --> 25:09.673
- Mike, you're up next.

25:09.717 --> 25:13.761
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:13.804 --> 25:15.221
- [exhales sharply]

25:15.264 --> 25:21.310
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:23.981 --> 25:26.357
- Mike, there's
a slight delamination

25:26.400 --> 25:28.943
that sticks out
a little bit right there.

25:28.986 --> 25:32.404
Being uneven, it did want
to lift through the cuts.

25:32.448 --> 25:34.323
But nonetheless,
the test is about the sharpness

25:34.367 --> 25:36.367
of your blade,
and it cuts, sir.

25:36.410 --> 25:38.327
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:38.371 --> 25:39.370
Clayton, you're up next.
You ready?

25:39.413 --> 25:40.371
- I am.

25:40.414 --> 25:47.211
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:52.552 --> 25:53.592
- Whoa.
- All right.

25:53.636 --> 25:54.593
- Whoa.

25:54.637 --> 25:56.762
- [laughing]

25:56.806 --> 25:59.390
- Clayton,
the edge geometry you have

25:59.433 --> 26:02.017
definitely made it easy
to wield the blade,

26:02.061 --> 26:04.311
complemented by the handle.

26:04.355 --> 26:07.648
It's a good fit.
This blade definitely cuts.

26:07.692 --> 26:09.316
- Thank you.

26:09.360 --> 26:11.694
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:11.737 --> 26:16.198
- Bladesmiths, the judges
have made their final decision.

26:16.242 --> 26:18.325
It's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

26:18.369 --> 26:22.830
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:26.460 --> 26:28.335
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:28.379 --> 26:32.339
- Bladesmiths, the judges
have made their final decision.

26:32.383 --> 26:34.091
It's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

26:34.135 --> 26:36.719
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:36.762 --> 26:38.387
Mike...

26:38.431 --> 26:41.682
your weapon
did not make the cut.

26:41.726 --> 26:43.684
- Mike, first off,
I want to thank you for showing

26:43.728 --> 26:46.437
that even when you have
a catastrophic blade failure...

26:46.480 --> 26:47.730
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:47.773 --> 26:49.940
You can find ways to fix it.

26:49.984 --> 26:52.943
But the time it took for you
to take care of those problems

26:52.987 --> 26:55.779
wasn't applied to taking care
of those first-round issues--

26:55.823 --> 26:57.489
that delamination,

26:57.533 --> 26:59.074
and that's why
we've got to let you go.

26:59.118 --> 27:00.826
- Thanks for the kind words.

27:00.870 --> 27:03.996
- Mike, please surrender
your weapon.

27:04.040 --> 27:06.290
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:06.334 --> 27:10.586
<i> - I tried my best,</i>
<i> but it wasn't good enough.</i>

27:10.630 --> 27:12.546
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:12.590 --> 27:16.884
But that teaches you,
you know, how to survive.

27:16.927 --> 27:20.346
There is a Russian saying...
[speaking in Russian]

27:20.389 --> 27:24.308
Which means
"survive against all odds,"

27:24.352 --> 27:25.768
<i> which I did.</i>

27:25.811 --> 27:28.604
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:28.648 --> 27:30.439
- Allen, Clayton,
congratulations.

27:30.483 --> 27:33.442
You both made it through
to the final round.

27:33.486 --> 27:34.818
When you showed up
at this Forge,

27:34.862 --> 27:36.487
you used our tools
and equipment

27:36.530 --> 27:39.323
to forge signature blades
in your own style.

27:39.367 --> 27:41.367
Now we're sending you back
to your home forge,

27:41.410 --> 27:42.910
where you will have five days

27:42.953 --> 27:45.746
to forge an iconic weapon
from history...

27:45.790 --> 27:48.707
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:48.751 --> 27:50.292
The boar spear.

27:50.336 --> 27:52.002
- [chuckles]

27:52.046 --> 27:54.546
<i> - Developed</i>
<i>as early as 700 A.D. in Europe,</i>

27:54.590 --> 27:57.758
<i> the boar spear was forged</i>
<i> for both combat and hunting.</i>

27:57.802 --> 27:59.343
<i> Known at the time</i>
<i> as a bar-spere,</i>

27:59.387 --> 28:01.845
<i> the weapon was about</i>
<i> 5 to 6 feet long</i>

28:01.889 --> 28:04.765
<i> and featured a pair of lugs</i>
<i> below the leaf-shaped blade.</i>

28:04.809 --> 28:07.101
<i> When hunting, the lugs</i>
<i> would stop a speared boar</i>

28:07.144 --> 28:08.769
<i> from running</i>
<i> up the length of the weapon</i>

28:08.813 --> 28:10.979
<i> and attacking the user.</i>

28:11.023 --> 28:13.524
<i> In combat,</i>
<i> the lugs could be used to hook</i>

28:13.567 --> 28:15.526
<i> and pull away enemy shields.</i>

28:15.569 --> 28:17.778
<i> The blade of the spear</i>
<i> could be decorated,</i>

28:17.822 --> 28:20.906
<i> with some featuring finely</i>
<i> engraved scenes of hunts.</i>

28:20.950 --> 28:23.117
<i> On the first season</i>
<i> of "Game of Thrones,"</i>

28:23.160 --> 28:25.327
<i> King Robert Baratheon</i>
<i> carried a boar spear</i>

28:25.371 --> 28:27.371
<i> on his final boar hunt.</i>

28:27.415 --> 28:30.040
At the end of five days,
you will return to this Forge

28:30.084 --> 28:32.376
and present
your completed boar spears

28:32.420 --> 28:34.044
to our panel of expert judges.

28:34.088 --> 28:37.631
Only after they have vigorously
tested those weapons

28:37.675 --> 28:39.717
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

28:39.760 --> 28:43.178
who also walks away
with a check for $10,000.

28:43.222 --> 28:44.430
Good luck, bladesmiths.

28:44.473 --> 28:46.849
We'll see you in five days.

28:46.892 --> 28:48.475
both:
Good luck.

28:48.519 --> 28:54.648
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:54.692 --> 28:56.358
- It's day one.

28:56.402 --> 28:58.318
Feels pretty good
to be back at the home forge.

28:58.362 --> 29:00.404
This is gonna be the start
of my Damascus layers.

29:00.448 --> 29:01.989
We're just alternating

29:02.032 --> 29:03.574
two different types of steel
together here.

29:03.617 --> 29:05.325
Cover.

29:05.369 --> 29:07.661
The plan for today
is to get a billet welded up,

29:07.705 --> 29:09.246
<i> get it drawn out.</i>

29:09.290 --> 29:10.622
I usually don't do billets
this big.

29:10.666 --> 29:12.166
It's sagging a lot
in the forge.

29:12.209 --> 29:15.127
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

29:15.171 --> 29:18.505
It's real exhausting being out
here in the Arizona heat.

29:18.549 --> 29:20.716
<i> It's upwards</i>
<i> of 100 degrees today,</i>

29:20.760 --> 29:22.634
<i> and it's gonna stay at least</i>
<i> that hot the rest of the week,</i>

29:22.678 --> 29:24.470
<i> so we just got to keep</i>
<i> moving slow,</i>

29:24.513 --> 29:26.221
<i> paying attention</i>
<i> to what we're doing,</i>

29:26.265 --> 29:27.931
and hopefully get the job done.

29:27.975 --> 29:29.808
<i> - It's day one.</i>

29:29.852 --> 29:31.769
<i> I'm excited</i>
<i> to have just made it this far</i>

29:31.812 --> 29:34.313
and get to actually do
the entire challenge.

29:34.356 --> 29:35.981
<i> The socket</i>
<i> is the part of the spear</i>

29:36.025 --> 29:38.358
<i>that you insert the shaft into.</i>

29:38.402 --> 29:40.110
I haven't ever made
a socket before,

29:40.154 --> 29:41.904
<i> so it's</i>
<i> a little nerve-racking,</i>

29:41.947 --> 29:43.989
but I'm excited to try it.

29:44.033 --> 29:46.700
I'm gonna start forming
a nice, thin triangular shape,

29:46.744 --> 29:48.285
<i> and then</i>
<i> I'm going to hammer it around</i>

29:48.329 --> 29:50.537
<i> into a circular cone shape.</i>

29:50.581 --> 29:52.790
Now I have to be super careful,

29:52.833 --> 29:54.625
<i>because the metal in the socket</i>
<i> is very thin.</i>

29:54.668 --> 29:56.376
<i> If this metal gets too hot,</i>

29:56.420 --> 29:58.545
it's gonna just kind of melt
and crumble away.

29:58.589 --> 30:00.297
All right,
it looks like a socket.

30:00.341 --> 30:02.591
Hopefully, it'll stay looking
like a socket.

30:02.635 --> 30:04.009
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:04.053 --> 30:05.594
<i> - Day two--</i>
<i> I really need</i>

30:05.638 --> 30:07.387
<i> to figure out</i>
<i> the design of the lugs.</i>

30:07.431 --> 30:08.972
Boars are pretty strong animals,
so if they don't have

30:09.016 --> 30:11.225
a wide enough cross-section,
they could just end up

30:11.268 --> 30:13.352
running that through
their body themselves.

30:13.395 --> 30:14.728
One of the ways I could do it

30:14.772 --> 30:16.480
is cutting a section
of the pipe out

30:16.524 --> 30:17.898
and bending it out.

30:17.942 --> 30:19.483
<i> It's gonna take a lot of work,</i>

30:19.527 --> 30:20.818
but it's something
that needs to be done.

30:20.861 --> 30:22.236
I'm battling the clock
on this one.

30:22.279 --> 30:24.988
[machinery whirring]

30:25.032 --> 30:27.533
I've decided to put my lugs
perpendicular to my blade.

30:27.576 --> 30:29.618
<i> It just made more sense</i>
<i> to have them perpendicular</i>

30:29.662 --> 30:31.161
<i> to stop the spear</i>
<i> from over-penetrating.</i>

30:31.205 --> 30:32.621
<i> It should work.</i>

30:32.665 --> 30:34.832
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:34.875 --> 30:36.416
<i> - It's day three.</i>

30:36.460 --> 30:38.085
<i> Time's really crunched.</i>

30:38.128 --> 30:39.753
I'm just really behind
the eight ball--

30:39.797 --> 30:41.880
getting the lugs
on the spear shaft.

30:41.924 --> 30:44.091
[motor sputtering]

30:44.134 --> 30:47.219
Oh, man.

30:47.263 --> 30:49.471
I believe
my blower has just died.

30:49.515 --> 30:52.349
<i> My forge burnt out.</i>
<i> The engine died.</i>

30:52.393 --> 30:54.434
Now I'm gonna have to find
a replacement.

30:54.478 --> 30:55.978
<i> There's still a lot to do.</i>

30:56.021 --> 30:57.688
I am literally running
to the store

30:57.731 --> 30:59.606
to buy another blower.
[tires squealing]

30:59.650 --> 31:02.651
<i> Things just really</i>
<i> are not going my way today.</i>

31:02.695 --> 31:03.819
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:07.449 --> 31:09.157
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:09.201 --> 31:10.951
<i> - My forge burnt out.</i>

31:10.995 --> 31:12.452
<i> The engine died.</i>
[tires screech]

31:12.496 --> 31:14.246
<i> Had to run out and lose time.</i>

31:14.290 --> 31:15.289
<i> I had to get a new motor.</i>

31:15.332 --> 31:16.748
With all these setbacks,

31:16.792 --> 31:19.084
I'm starting to be
a bit worried.

31:19.128 --> 31:21.753
[machinery humming]

31:21.797 --> 31:23.755
With the way things
have been going today,

31:23.799 --> 31:25.465
<i> we're coming down</i>
<i> to the wire on time here.</i>

31:25.509 --> 31:26.884
It could come back to bite me.

31:26.927 --> 31:29.303
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:29.346 --> 31:31.096
<i> - It's the last day.</i>

31:31.140 --> 31:33.557
<i> There's still a lot</i>
<i> of work to be done.</i>

31:33.601 --> 31:35.392
<i> So I'm getting ready</i>
<i> to quench the blade.</i>

31:35.436 --> 31:37.185
<i> I got to move my forge</i>
<i> into the shed.</i>

31:37.229 --> 31:39.062
<i> I need it as dark as possible</i>

31:39.106 --> 31:40.981
<i> to accurately judge</i>
<i> the temperature of the steel.</i>

31:41.025 --> 31:42.733
<i>As I'm trying to get this blade</i>
<i> up to an even temp,</i>

31:42.776 --> 31:44.234
<i> I'm checking for the color,</i>

31:44.278 --> 31:45.527
<i> I'm checking it</i>
<i> with the magnet...</i>

31:45.571 --> 31:47.154
Very close.

31:47.197 --> 31:48.614
<i> And making sure</i>
<i> I have a good, even heat</i>

31:48.657 --> 31:50.532
<i> by turning it</i>
<i> on and off the forge</i>

31:50.576 --> 31:51.867
<i>and taking it in and out of it.</i>

31:51.911 --> 31:54.453
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:54.496 --> 31:55.829
There's lots of things
that could go wrong

31:55.873 --> 31:56.914
coming out of the quench.

31:56.957 --> 31:58.957
<i> It could have a horrible warp.</i>

31:59.001 --> 32:01.126
If the quench goes wrong,
I'm kind of SOL.

32:01.170 --> 32:04.671
<i> I don't have a lot of time</i>
<i> to start a new project.</i>

32:04.715 --> 32:06.340
<i> It's as straight</i>
<i> as I could get it.</i>

32:06.383 --> 32:08.133
I'll go grab a file
and rub it on there

32:08.177 --> 32:09.885
for hardness.

32:09.929 --> 32:11.428
We have good conversion.

32:11.472 --> 32:12.888
Yeah, I feel pretty confident
right now.

32:12.932 --> 32:16.600
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:16.644 --> 32:19.061
Well,
we've done what we can done.

32:19.104 --> 32:20.896
It's solid.

32:20.940 --> 32:22.564
<i> I'm pretty confident</i>
<i> the spear will stand up</i>

32:22.608 --> 32:24.107
<i> to the judges' tests.</i>

32:24.151 --> 32:25.192
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:25.235 --> 32:26.485
<i> - It's day five.</i>

32:26.528 --> 32:28.195
<i> Well, my vision for this</i>

32:28.238 --> 32:30.489
<i> is to have a nice, dark pole.</i>

32:30.532 --> 32:33.533
<i>We'll heat it up with the torch</i>
<i> until it turns black,</i>

32:33.577 --> 32:36.828
and then I'm going to rub
some beeswax from my own bees.

32:36.872 --> 32:38.455
<i> Here in my backyard</i>

32:38.499 --> 32:40.082
<i> is where I keep my bees.</i>

32:40.125 --> 32:42.042
I do get a little bit
of honey every year,

32:42.086 --> 32:45.545
but I mostly keep them
for the fun of it.

32:45.589 --> 32:47.756
The beeswax--
it'll kind of melt in there

32:47.800 --> 32:50.175
and treat the wood
and give it a nice sheen.

32:50.219 --> 32:51.927
<i> Time's still rolling.</i>

32:51.971 --> 32:53.261
<i> I'm gonna need</i>
<i> to use every minute</i>

32:53.305 --> 32:54.513
<i> to get this thing</i>
<i> looking great.</i>

32:54.556 --> 32:56.390
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:56.433 --> 32:58.517
I have just sharpened
the boar spear.

32:58.560 --> 33:00.227
I'm thinking it's time
for a little test

33:00.270 --> 33:01.937
before I put it on the pole.

33:01.981 --> 33:03.605
My kids made this great boar.

33:03.649 --> 33:05.482
<i> [animal grunts]</i>

33:05.526 --> 33:08.944
I'm ready to see this boar spear
cut, slice, and stab.

33:08.988 --> 33:13.490
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

33:13.534 --> 33:15.283
Feels good to me.

33:15.327 --> 33:18.161
I'm ready to see what
the judges have planned.

33:18.205 --> 33:21.081
<i> [intense percussive music]</i>

33:21.125 --> 33:24.334
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

33:24.378 --> 33:26.211
- Bladesmiths,
welcome back to the Forge.

33:26.255 --> 33:29.381
You've had five days at home
to work on your boar spears.

33:29.425 --> 33:31.091
Clayton.
How did it go?

33:31.135 --> 33:32.467
- My spear is constructed

33:32.511 --> 33:35.012
with a 36-layer crushed
Damascus billet.

33:35.055 --> 33:36.722
<i> To form the socket,</i>

33:36.765 --> 33:38.765
<i> I just used a piece</i>
<i> of 1/8-inch wall pipe</i>

33:38.809 --> 33:40.350
<i> I forge-welded</i>
<i> onto the Damascus.</i>

33:40.394 --> 33:42.352
<i> And the shaft is ash.</i>

33:42.396 --> 33:44.855
Just went with, like, a simple
round handle on that, so, yeah.

33:44.898 --> 33:46.523
- Very cool.

33:46.567 --> 33:48.442
Allen, tell us a little bit
about your blade.

33:48.485 --> 33:50.861
- All right, well,
I forged the spear out of W-2

33:50.904 --> 33:53.238
<i> and forge-welded the socket</i>

33:53.282 --> 33:55.365
<i> and then welded on</i>
<i> some kind of pretty wings</i>

33:55.409 --> 33:57.200
<i> for some lugs.</i>

33:57.244 --> 34:00.912
I used ash that's blackened
with fire for the shaft.

34:00.956 --> 34:04.666
- Well, gentlemen, both of your
boar spears look very deadly.

34:04.710 --> 34:06.835
But looks are secondary
to performance.

34:06.879 --> 34:10.130
Your weapons will now be put
through a series of three tests.

34:10.174 --> 34:12.090
Doug?

34:12.134 --> 34:14.634
- Bladesmiths,
this is the sharpness test.

34:14.678 --> 34:16.511
To see how sharp
your boar spears are,

34:16.555 --> 34:18.388
we will test
the tip and the edge

34:18.432 --> 34:20.348
by stabbing and slashing
through these sandbags.

34:20.392 --> 34:21.892
- All right.
- Clayton, you're up first.

34:21.935 --> 34:24.019
You ready?
- I'm ready.

34:24.063 --> 34:25.562
<i> It's really exciting</i>
<i> to have a weapon I've made</i>

34:25.606 --> 34:27.064
<i> being tested this way.</i>

34:27.107 --> 34:28.523
<i> Normally,</i>
<i> I make 'em real pretty,</i>

34:28.567 --> 34:30.984
and very rarely
does somebody actually purchase

34:31.028 --> 34:32.611
<i> a functional piece</i>
<i> that they're gonna go out</i>

34:32.654 --> 34:34.738
and just tear to pieces
and really put it to the test.

34:34.782 --> 34:41.620
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:45.876 --> 34:47.375
[chuckling]

34:47.419 --> 34:51.004
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:51.048 --> 34:54.216
- Well, Clayton,
the balance of your tip

34:54.259 --> 34:56.134
lends itself to stabbing.

34:56.178 --> 34:59.638
Your edge lacerated cleanly
on the moving sandbag.

34:59.681 --> 35:02.432
What surprised me
was the positioning of your lug.

35:02.476 --> 35:04.935
Traditionally,
they have it crosswise this way,

35:04.978 --> 35:06.144
but you have it this way.

35:06.188 --> 35:08.021
Because of that,
it was hard to index

35:08.065 --> 35:10.023
when you're cutting through.

35:10.067 --> 35:12.359
But then again,
it will cut.

35:12.402 --> 35:14.569
- Thank you.
- Allen, you're next. Ready?

35:14.613 --> 35:15.821
- Oh, yeah.

35:15.864 --> 35:22.702
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:34.466 --> 35:37.300
- Well, Allen, your spear
feels good to hold on to.

35:37.344 --> 35:39.636
It was easy to index
and know where the edge was.

35:39.680 --> 35:42.430
So there was a nice slash
that I could penetrate through,

35:42.474 --> 35:44.558
and in the thrust,
it felt good in the hand.

35:44.601 --> 35:45.892
- All right.

35:45.936 --> 35:48.436
- I can see a little bow
in your handle.

35:48.480 --> 35:51.523
But when we're talking
about the sharpness test,

35:51.567 --> 35:53.316
this, sir, will cut.

35:53.360 --> 35:55.402
- All right.

35:55.445 --> 35:57.779
- Next up is the kill test.

35:57.823 --> 36:01.283
To see what kind of lethal
damage your weapon can do,

36:01.326 --> 36:04.035
I will deliver lethal blows
to this wild-boar carcass.

36:04.079 --> 36:05.245
Clayton, you're up first.

36:05.289 --> 36:06.746
Are you ready?
- Absolutely.

36:06.790 --> 36:08.373
<i> The first thing</i>
<i> that went through my mind</i>

36:08.417 --> 36:10.292
is, "Oh, man, it still has
all its hair on it,

36:10.335 --> 36:11.835
"and that really can impede

36:11.879 --> 36:13.837
the cutting ability
of an edged tool."

36:13.881 --> 36:15.046
And after that, I was like,
"Wow, they got a real boar.

36:15.090 --> 36:16.214
This is gonna be pretty cool."

36:16.258 --> 36:23.096
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:28.061 --> 36:29.686
[chuckles]

36:29.730 --> 36:33.148
- Well, Clayton,
your boar spear right here

36:33.192 --> 36:35.525
did very well on the thrust,

36:35.569 --> 36:37.068
penetrating
all the way through

36:37.112 --> 36:41.114
on the low line
and on the high line.

36:41.158 --> 36:44.618
On the edge,
it lacerated cleanly,

36:44.661 --> 36:46.203
and testing the other side,

36:46.246 --> 36:48.288
it cut all the way
through the spine.

36:48.332 --> 36:50.415
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:50.459 --> 36:52.417
This, sir, will kill.

36:52.461 --> 36:54.336
Good job.
- Thank you.

36:54.379 --> 36:55.879
- Allen, you're next.
You ready?

36:55.923 --> 36:57.297
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's do this.

36:57.341 --> 37:04.179
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

37:19.529 --> 37:21.446
- Well, Allen,
let's talk about your blade.

37:21.490 --> 37:24.491
On the thrust, it penetrated
all the way through.

37:24.534 --> 37:27.535
On the laceration
on one side of your edge,

37:27.579 --> 37:29.704
boy, wow,
it almost sliced

37:29.748 --> 37:31.998
<i>all the way through.</i>

37:32.042 --> 37:36.544
On your other edge,
it lacerated through the spine.

37:36.588 --> 37:38.713
This spear, sir, will kill.

37:38.757 --> 37:40.173
- All right.

37:40.217 --> 37:42.842
- Next up is
the strength test. Dave?

37:42.886 --> 37:44.844
- Gentlemen,
it's been said that the sword

37:44.888 --> 37:47.681
is the prince of all weapons,
but the spear is the king.

37:47.724 --> 37:49.683
<i>To test the strength</i>
<i>of your boar spears,</i>

37:49.726 --> 37:51.393
<i>I'm gonna load them</i>
<i>into our air cannon here</i>

37:51.436 --> 37:53.436
<i>and fire them</i>
<i>into this wooden target.</i>

37:53.480 --> 37:55.355
- Oh, my.
- [laughs]

37:55.399 --> 37:58.358
- This is a crazy test.
It's a fun test.

37:58.402 --> 38:01.194
Thrilled to see it go down.
I just can't wait.

38:01.238 --> 38:02.904
- We'll see
how deep it penetrates,

38:02.948 --> 38:04.823
how well it holds up,
and if it holds up

38:04.866 --> 38:06.574
while I remove the spear
from the target.

38:06.618 --> 38:08.493
- Awesome.
- Clayton, you're up first.

38:08.537 --> 38:10.036
You ready?
- I am.

38:10.080 --> 38:12.455
- All right, let's do this.

38:12.499 --> 38:14.207
<i> - Oh, man.</i>

38:14.251 --> 38:16.334
I'm just hoping
that my handle stays together.

38:16.378 --> 38:18.003
<i> I'm hoping</i>
<i>that after it impacts the wood,</i>

38:18.046 --> 38:19.504
that it doesn't break
the blade off

38:19.548 --> 38:20.672
or something like that.

38:20.716 --> 38:27.554
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:29.474 --> 38:31.349
- In...

38:31.393 --> 38:33.435
three...

38:33.478 --> 38:35.603
two...

38:35.647 --> 38:36.938
one.

38:36.982 --> 38:39.774
[loud hissing]

38:41.361 --> 38:46.865
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:46.908 --> 38:48.116
[exhales sharply]

38:48.160 --> 38:54.998
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:56.293 --> 38:58.418
- [exhales deeply]

38:58.462 --> 39:00.670
- Well, Clayton,
your spear really dug in deep.

39:00.714 --> 39:02.172
It went in about 4 inches.

39:02.215 --> 39:03.673
Came out fine.

39:03.717 --> 39:06.634
Everything's still tight
and dialed in.

39:06.678 --> 39:08.887
This is interesting,
being offset.

39:08.930 --> 39:10.388
- Being that it's a boar spear,

39:10.432 --> 39:12.182
I wanted to make sure
that whatever laceration

39:12.225 --> 39:14.351
the blade produced
on the animal

39:14.394 --> 39:16.978
<i> wasn't wide enough to allow</i>
<i> the wings to come through,</i>

39:17.022 --> 39:19.898
and the best way to do that was
just make them perpendicular.

39:19.941 --> 39:22.108
- All right, nicely done.
- Thank you.

39:22.152 --> 39:23.985
- Allen, you're up.

39:24.029 --> 39:28.239
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:28.283 --> 39:29.991
Got a little warp
in your shaft.

39:30.035 --> 39:32.035
I'm picking it up
in the tube there,

39:32.079 --> 39:34.996
so hopefully
it'll all fly well.

39:35.040 --> 39:36.539
<i> - I'm not horribly concerned,</i>

39:36.583 --> 39:39.167
but it's certainly
not making me thrilled.

39:39.211 --> 39:42.670
- All right, in three,
two, one.

39:42.714 --> 39:44.839
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:48.470 --> 39:52.055
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:52.099 --> 39:54.432
- All right,
in three...

39:54.476 --> 39:56.309
two...

39:56.353 --> 39:57.769
one.

39:57.813 --> 39:59.187
[loud hissing]

39:59.231 --> 40:06.069
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

40:19.376 --> 40:21.626
All right, Allen.
That buried itself quite nicely.

40:21.670 --> 40:24.754
It went into about--there,
again, about 4 inches deep.

40:24.798 --> 40:26.673
<i> Like the leaf shape on this.</i>

40:26.716 --> 40:28.883
<i> I like the fact that</i>
<i> you hand-hammered the socket.</i>

40:28.927 --> 40:31.219
I was kind of worried
when I put this in our machine

40:31.263 --> 40:33.930
that slight warp in your shaft
there would bind up,

40:33.974 --> 40:35.849
but not a problem.

40:35.892 --> 40:38.393
Good job.
- Thank you.

40:38.437 --> 40:40.478
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

40:40.522 --> 40:43.690
- Bladesmiths, the judges have
completed their deliberation,

40:43.733 --> 40:45.024
and they've made
a final decision.

40:45.068 --> 40:46.860
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

40:46.903 --> 40:49.237
However, before I tell you
what that decision is,

40:49.281 --> 40:52.323
they have some comments
for both of you. Jason?

40:52.367 --> 40:56.870
- Allen, I appreciated how your
spear performed on the boar.

40:56.913 --> 40:59.622
It was very impressive,
the cut that it made.

40:59.666 --> 41:02.000
<i> It cut really deep.</i>
<i> It went through the spine.</i>

41:02.043 --> 41:05.628
So, well designed as a weapon.
- Thank you.

41:05.672 --> 41:07.255
- Dave?

41:07.299 --> 41:08.298
- Clayton,
I like the look on the Damascus,

41:08.341 --> 41:10.091
<i> in the point of your spear.</i>

41:10.135 --> 41:11.759
<i> It makes for a very dramatic</i>
<i> look on that.</i>

41:11.803 --> 41:13.970
<i> It certainly got</i>
<i> amazing penetration</i>

41:14.014 --> 41:16.306
<i> in the tests against the boar.</i>

41:16.349 --> 41:18.933
<i> The thing that concerns me</i>
<i> is the shape of your blade.</i>

41:18.977 --> 41:20.894
<i> It doesn't get wider</i>
<i> at the base</i>

41:20.937 --> 41:23.480
<i> or leaf out the way</i>
<i> a boar spear typically does,</i>

41:23.523 --> 41:24.689
but nicely done.

41:24.733 --> 41:26.608
- Thank you.

41:26.651 --> 41:29.360
- Bladesmiths,
both of you have turned in

41:29.404 --> 41:31.571
fantastic boar spears.

41:31.615 --> 41:33.781
However,
in this arena of competition,

41:33.825 --> 41:35.825
there can only be one
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:35.869 --> 41:41.080
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:41.124 --> 41:43.458
- Allen,
congratulations.

41:43.502 --> 41:45.084
You are
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

41:45.128 --> 41:47.712
- Congratulations.
- You did awesome.

41:47.756 --> 41:51.174
- Clayton, your boar spear
did not make the cut.

41:51.218 --> 41:54.260
- Clayton, this was not
an easy decision to make.

41:54.304 --> 41:55.803
Because of your
perpendicular lugs,

41:55.847 --> 41:58.348
it was hard to visually index
your blade,

41:58.391 --> 42:00.767
<i> meaning it's hard to tell</i>
<i> where the cutting edge is.</i>

42:00.810 --> 42:03.311
<i> That makes it</i>
<i> a less effective weapon.</i>

42:03.355 --> 42:05.271
And for that,
we had to let you go.

42:05.315 --> 42:06.856
- I understand.

42:06.900 --> 42:09.692
- Clayton,
please surrender your weapon.

42:09.736 --> 42:12.237
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:12.280 --> 42:13.696
<i> - Right now, obviously,</i>
<i> I'm a little bit disappointed,</i>

42:13.740 --> 42:15.865
but this
is the first spear I made,

42:15.909 --> 42:17.867
<i> and for me,</i>
<i> it's really important</i>

42:17.911 --> 42:19.619
that it was such a tight race.

42:19.663 --> 42:21.412
I don't want it to be anything
that I handed him

42:21.456 --> 42:23.039
or anything
that he would've handed me.

42:23.083 --> 42:25.166
<i> Allen is a deserving champion.</i>

42:25.210 --> 42:26.709
- Allen, congratulations.

42:26.753 --> 42:28.419
You are
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

42:28.463 --> 42:30.797
and with that comes
a check for $10,000.

42:30.840 --> 42:31.923
Congratulations.

42:31.967 --> 42:35.552
[applause]
- Thank you.

42:35.595 --> 42:37.011
- You know, what I really
appreciate about that

42:37.055 --> 42:39.430
is the fact
that you took the time

42:39.474 --> 42:41.599
to actually hammer
that cone out.

42:41.643 --> 42:43.851
Making that socket is
a really nice touch

42:43.895 --> 42:45.144
on any kind
of traditional spear.

42:45.188 --> 42:46.646
Well done.

42:46.690 --> 42:48.856
- I am the "Forged in Fire"
champion.

42:48.900 --> 42:50.650
I cannot believe it.

42:50.694 --> 42:52.610
<i> I had no idea</i>
<i> if it was gonna be me or him,</i>

42:52.654 --> 42:54.821
and it was me.

42:54.864 --> 42:56.864
<i> I'm betting being</i>
<i> a "Forged in Fire" champion's</i>

42:56.908 --> 42:59.576
<i> gonna help this</i>
<i> stay-at-home dad/knife maker</i>

42:59.619 --> 43:02.328
<i> convince a few people that</i>
<i> they should try out my blades.</i>

43:02.372 --> 43:03.621
It's great.
[chuckles]

43:03.665 --> 43:10.003
<i> ♪ ♪</i>
